Kowloon's Jade Magistracy has operational interest in Flood Court Remnants primarily through the
hydraulic engineering records they preserve. Khardaan's cistern verge infrastructure—the mechanical
core managing water pressure for tomb-sealing operations—represents sophisticated pre-collapse
hydraulic engineering whose operational principles remain relevant for Kowloon's own water
management challenges. Access requires framing requests as water-right cases within the Court's
existing procedural framework rather than archival protocol. Kowloon's delegation attempted this
and produced partial results. The relevant engineering notes are in the Jade Magistracy's restricted
technical archive.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess's scholarly interest in the Flood Court Remnants is legal-historical: the Court represents
a judicial tradition predating all five current city governments whose procedural principles may
establish precedents relevant to contemporary water-right disputes. The Syndic Council's specific
interest is in the Charter of Passage analog the Court enforced—the principle that water access
rights established by original charter cannot be overridden by subsequent administrative decisions
regardless of practical resource constraints. If this principle has continuous legal force through
surviving records, it would establish the oldest known precedent for the anti-sealed-classification
doctrine Kiess's own charter embodies. Kiess has assigned a scholar-clerk to the formal consultation
process; the process is ongoing and has produced two partial records relevant to the precedent
question.

flags RAKUEN
